│ THOUGHT                                                                                                                                                                                  │
│ The user wants me to fix an LLVM miscompilation where `instcombine` incorrectly transforms `select(fcmp ole %x, 0), -%x, %x` into `fabs(%x)`. This is incorrect for negative SNaN        │
│ inputs.                                                                                                                                                                                  │
│                                                                                                                                                                                          │
│ My previous attempts have failed the regression tests in `test/Transforms/InstCombine/fabs.ll`. The failing test case is `select_fcmp_ole_zero_no_nnan_input_nofpclass_nan`, which has a │
│ `nofpclass(nan)` attribute on the input. This attribute guarantees the input is not a NaN, so the transformation to `fabs` should be legal. My patches have been preventing this legal   │
│ transformation.                                                                                                                                                                          │
│                                                                                                                                                                                          │
│ The core issue is that the transformation to `fabs` is only valid if the operand `X` is known not to be a NaN. The predicates `FCMP_OLE` and `FCMP_OGT` are "ordered" and will evaluate  │
│ to `false` on NaN inputs, causing a negative SNaN to be passed through the `select`, while `fabs` would have returned a positive SNaN. The "unordered" predicates `FCMP_ULE` and         │
│ `FCMP_UGT` are also problematic due to how they handle SNaNs vs. QNaNs.                                                                                                                  │
│                                                                                                                                                                                          │
│ The correct fix is to allow this transformation only when we can prove that the input `X` is not a NaN. The `nnan` fast-math flag is one way to establish this. Another is through       │
│ value-tracking analysis.                                                                                                                                                                 │
│                                                                                                                                                                                          │
│ The utility `llvm::isKnownNeverNaN(X)` is designed for this purpose. It checks for `nnan` flags and `nofpclass` attributes. My previous attempts to use this function failed, likely due │
│ to incorrect arguments or context. The function signature is `bool isKnownNeverNaN(const Value *V, ...)`. It can take a `DataLayout` and other analysis results, but the simplest form   │
│ just takes the `Value *`.                                                                                                                                                                │
│                                                                                                                                                                                          │
│ The transformation is valid if the `select` instruction has the `nnan` flag, or if the operand `X` is known to be not a NaN. Therefore, the condition should be `SI.hasNoNaNs() ||       │
│ llvm::isKnownNeverNaN(X)`.                                                                                                                                                               │
│                                                                                                                                                                                          │
│ I will apply this logic to the two problematic transformations in `foldSelectWithFCmpToFabs` in `llvm/lib/Transforms/InstCombine/InstCombineSelect.cpp`.                                 │
│                                                                                                                                                                                          │
│ ```bash                                                                                                                                                                                  │
│ sed -i -e '2797s/if (!Swap/if ((SI.hasNoNaNs() || llvm::isKnownNeverNaN(X)) \&\& !Swap/' -e '2801s/if (Swap/if ((SI.hasNoNaNs() || llvm::isKnownNeverNaN(X)) \&\& Swap/'                 │
│ llvm/lib/Transforms/InstCombine/InstCombineSelect.cpp                                                                                                                                    │
│ ```                                                                                                                                                                                      │
