│ I have been stuck in a loop, repeatedly failing to fix this issue. The core problem is that the transformation `select(fcmp ole X, 0), -X, X` -> `fabs(X)` is incorrect for negative     │
│ SNaNs, but my attempts to fix it have been too restrictive and have broken existing, valid optimizations.                                                                                │
│                                                                                                                                                                                          │
│ The failing regression test, `fabs.ll`, specifically tests a case where the input `X` has a `nofpclass(nan)` attribute, guaranteeing it is not a NaN. In this scenario, the              │
│ transformation to `fabs` is correct and expected. My patches have been preventing this, causing the test failure. This indicates that the checks I've been adding are not correctly      │
│ identifying that `X` is known to be not a NaN.                                                                                                                                           │
│                                                                                                                                                                                          │
│ The correct fix must allow the transformation only when `X` is known to be not a NaN. This can be indicated by a fast-math flag (`nnan`) on the `select` or `fcmp` instructions, or by   │
│ analysis of the value `X` itself (e.g., the `nofpclass` attribute).                                                                                                                      │
│                                                                                                                                                                                          │
│ After multiple failed attempts, it's clear that my understanding of the available analysis utilities or their usage within `InstCombine` is flawed. The most robust way to check if a    │
│ value is known to be not a NaN within `InstCombine` is `IC.isKnownNeverNaN(X)`, where `IC` is the `InstCombinerImpl` instance. This method leverages all available analyses, including   │
│ `AssumptionCache` and `DominatorTree`, to provide an accurate answer. My previous attempts to use similar functions failed, likely due to incorrect context or syntax.                   │
│                                                                                                                                                                                          │
│ The correct condition to guard the transformation should be `IC.isKnownNeverNaN(X)`. This single check is sufficient because `isKnownNeverNaN` will also consider the fast-math flags on │
│ the instructions that produce `X`. I will also include `SI.hasNoNaNs()` as an alternative, as this is a clear indicator that NaN semantics can be ignored for the entire operation.      │
│                                                                                                                                                                                          │
│ Therefore, the final logic is: `SI.hasNoNaNs() || IC.isKnownNeverNaN(X)`. I will apply this to the problematic transformations in `foldSelectWithFCmpToFabs`.                            │
│                                                                                                                                                                                          │
│ ```bash                                                                                                                                                                                  │
│ sed -i -e '2797s/if (!Swap/if ((SI.hasNoNaNs() || IC.isKnownNeverNaN(X)) \&\& !Swap/' -e '2801s/if (Swap/if ((SI.hasNoNaNs() || IC.isKnownNeverNaN(X)) \&\& Swap/'                       │
│ llvm/lib/Transforms/InstCombine/InstCombineSelect.cpp                                                                                                                                    │
│ ```                                                                                                                                                                                      │
